# Emily Desktop & Terminal UI Rules

## PySide6 Desktop App (emily_chat/)
- Main app is `emily_chat/app.py` with `emily_chat/main.py` as the entry point
- Uses Qt's signal/slot pattern for inter-component communication — never poll in the UI thread
- Themes are QSS stylesheets in `emily_chat/assets/themes/` (dark.qss, light.qss)
- Keep UI logic in controller (`emily_chat/controller.py`), not in widget classes

### Component Rules
- One widget class per file in `emily_chat/ui/`
- Widget filenames match widget class names (snake_case file, PascalCase class)
- Heavy computation (LLM calls, embedding, file parsing) must run in a worker thread via `QThreadPool` or `asyncio.to_thread` — never block the UI thread
- Markdown rendering goes through `emily_chat/ui/markdown_renderer.py`

### Model Providers
- Provider implementations live in `emily_chat/models/` (openai, anthropic, ollama, etc.)
- All providers must implement the same interface for the auto_router to dispatch to them
- Cost tracking via `emily_chat/models/cost_tracker.py`

## Textual TUI (ui/)
- Brain dashboard: `ui/brain/dashboard.py` — shows FSM state, active agents, memory
- Voice dashboard: `ui/voice/dashboard.py` — shows audio pipeline, TTS state
- Terminal app: `ui/terminal/app.py` — interactive conversation interface

### Textual Conventions
- Use Textual's reactive attributes for state that drives UI updates
- CSS styling in `.tcss` files co-located with the app
- Widgets compose via `yield` in `compose()` — keep the widget tree shallow
- Use `work()` decorator for async operations that update the UI
